<DOC><DOCNO> AP890610-0024 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0952EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-SevereStorm 1stLd-Writethru a0421 06-10 0382</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Severe Storm, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0421,0388</SECOND><HEAD>Severe Storm Spawns Philadelphia Tornado; 1 Dead</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The body...', to UPDATE with identity of victim,CORRECT her age to 13 sted 15.</HEAD><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A storm slammed Philadelphia with heavy rain,winds up to 120 mph and a tornado, disrupting power to thousands ofcustomers and leaving one person dead and one seriously injured.   A suspected tornado in Delaware's New Castle County, across thestate line southeast of Philadelphia, destroyed at least one houseand a school gymnasium, damaged at least four other homes andknocked out power to about 1,000 customers Friday evening,authorities said. No injuries were reported.   The twister landed in Philadelphia's affluent Society Hillsection about 7:15 p.m. and slashed northeast for half a mile to theDelaware River, the National Weather Service said.   Police and witnesses said the funnel cloud then skipped acrossthe river and damaged a dozen houses in Camden, N.J. The weatherservice said it had not investigated the Camden damage and could notconfirm a tornado there.   The body of girl who apparently fell into a rain-swollentributary of Cobbs Creek in suburban Upper Darby during the stormwas found two miles downstream late Friday, said Upper DarbyTownship Detective Ron Lavin. The victim was identified today as13-year-old Alix Christina Lidle of Upper Darby.   Police said a man was blown into a Society Hill telephone booth.He was listed in stable but guarded condition with a head injuryearly today in the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania.   The north and west walls of a three-story parking garagecollapsed during the storm, damaging two parked vehicles and anearby house, police said.   Officer Michael Beren said a sudden darkness descended while hewas on patrol.   ``I couldn't see two feet in front of my face,'' he said. ``Itwas black and dark _ and then there was a roar.''   The tornado was 50 yards wide at points, the weather service said.   Philadelphia Electric Co. spokesman Michael Wood said about 4,500customers lost power for at least part of the evening.   A Camden family had to be evacuated from their home after a beamcrashed through the ceiling, said Camy Trinidad, a spokeswoman forthe Camden County Red Cross.</TEXT></DOC>